    <hr xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"/><p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="Body-investigation-hanging">8. A certain woman
    already has one child, which is a boy. She now expects a
    second child. What is the probability of it being a boy again,
    if we make the assumption that a baby being a boy or a girl are
    equally likely events?</p><hr xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"/>

    <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="aside">
      <p class="Body-box-no-indent">The assumption that a boy or a
      girl being born are equally likely events may not actually be
      true. However, probabilities can only be calculated and used
      to make predictions if it is assumed that outcomes are
      equally likely.</p>
    </div>
   
 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="ques-a--2-space-below">9. (a) A woman gets married
